      <td> 
        <div align="left"> 
          <p><font face="Verdana" size="-1"><b>Chapter 1: 
            Clear Skies</b><br></font>
            <font face="Verdana" size="-2">(by <a href="http://www.eqraid.org/stories/members.cgi?action=showprofile&login=ahaboo1">ahaboo1</a> <a href="mailto:ahaboo@pacbell.com?subject=Interactive Fiction"><img src="graphics/email.gif" border="0" alt="send e-mail"></a> 
, added on February 26, 2001  05:49 PM CT (US))</font></p>
        </div>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <br>
  <table width="90%" border="0" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="1">
    <tr> 
      <td> <font face="Verdana" size="-1">A drop of dew rushed down the green leaf.  It raced down as if knowing it would soon be disturbed.  The branch shook violently, the brush parted, the steed let lose a slight whiny as it caught its footing.  <br>"Ahh, clear skies," the rider mumbled to himself.  He took in a deep breath through his nose.  The scent, the scent of familiarity.  He had come home. <br>The journey he had been on had taken him several months but he was now home.  The quest was all behind him now, his ascension to his current status was a long hard task, but that was not on his mind at the moment.  He knew that soon he would be within the confines of the keep and again the longing feelings would burn again.  <br>Would she be there?  Had anything changed?  Word of Icewind Keep had not reached him in these many months away.  Uncertainty began to fill his mind.  The joy of his homecoming, clouded by old feelings.  <br>The gates seemed closed as he made his approach.  Off in the distance he could make out an Orc encampment, their shamens' fires begin to light up the sky as the sun set.  Seems as much as we tried the Orcs have never given up, there seemed to be an endess supply, he thought to himself.  <br>"Hail, old one," a voice from behind him spoke.<br>"Oldsalt, I knew you were near by your stench," he replied.<br>Oldsalt broke out into a robust laughter, exclaiming,  "you jumped so far out of your saddle, I thought you were taught to fly!"<br>He smiled, knowing he was had, "I see you are still attempting to learn the ways of your lost art, perhaps some day they will prove useful."<br>Laughing Oldsalt answers, "Perhaps, anyway I will see you soon.  You should not have trouble making it to the keep."<br>He waves farwell and continues his travels.  The fires from the keep burned bright.  He began to hear the rumblings of a town.  It was not so long ago, when Icewind Keep was barely a few lodges and tents.  Now success had brought prosperity.  One of the great doors opened as he drew near.<br>"Now it would be just like you to arrive as we are to begin our meal.  Welcome home my friend," said Aegirson as he reached around and delivered a big hug.  <br>"It has been too long old friend," he reciprocated.<br>Aegirson shouted.  "Go on they are expecting you.  Just save me some food for later!" <br>As he opened the door to the hall, he caught it.  The scent.  The smell of lilacs on a summers day.  The freshness of a spring morning.  A scent so cool, he could see with his eyes opened.  She had just walked by, she had to be close.  His pulse hastened.  His eyes alert.  He gulped.  The nervousness again.  She was here.  He would see her soon.<br>The room was busy, people scurring about tending to their duties.  Great men and women conversing.  Those seeking greatness hovering about.  The Great Hall filled with activity.  A smile broke across his face.  His mind filled with, what if's.<br>Ahh, how he longed for clear skies.</font></td>
    </tr>
