      <td> 
        <div align="left"> 
          <p><font face="Verdana" size="-1"><b>Chapter 4: 
            Night Watch</b><br></font>
            <font face="Verdana" size="-2">(by <a href="http://www.eqraid.org/stories/members.cgi?action=showprofile&login=ahaboo1">ahaboo1</a> <a href="mailto:ahaboo@pacbell.com?subject=Interactive Fiction"><img src="graphics/email.gif" border="0" alt="send e-mail"></a> 
, added on March 6, 2001  05:53 PM CT (US))</font></p>
        </div>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <br>
  <table width="90%" border="0" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="1">
    <tr> 
      <td> <font face="Verdana" size="-1">The noise, chatter, the living of the room filled his senses.  The room was alive.  He had spent much of the past several months preparing for his ascension to his rank.  Now was the time to experience the living again.  His heart continue to yearn, burning in a way, unsatisfied.  He knew she had been here.  He sensed her.  He knew.  However, he did not want to seem obvious, he did not want to share.  If those around him could only read his face it would be as apparent as getting wet in a storm.  He kept his manner stoic.  There will come a time, a moment when it would be right, a moment when he would be sure.  He would let her know.<br>The activity of the evening became too much for him.  Too much, too fast.  Still she was not here.  No satisfation to steal a glance.  No knowing if he could read her face, her manner.  With a smile he excused himself from the table.  His comrades extending their good will.<br>As he made his way from the Hall, he spoted a squire making his way.  They both nodded to one another.  The squire in gallant fashion.  He smiled as the squire past.  Dreams of youth.  He thought, he knew, the lesson in life he had come to know.  It was not the knowing.  It was not the experience.  It was not the fame, possession, or material things one strived to obtain.  Life, a true life to oneself he had come to know was to follow ones heart.  Only recently had he began to listen.  All these years.  All the battles.  The desire to prove oneself.  To who?  To what end?  The calling of the heart.  <br>As he found himself on the walls of Icewind Keep, he heard a familiar voice.<br>"Sounds fairly livily in there tonite," commented McMad.<br>"Livily indeed, my friend.  It is good to see you again," he responded extending his arm.<br>Taking the arm with his, "Aye too long indeed," McMad concluded.<br>"McMad my journey has my mind racing still.  May I assume the watch?" he asked.<br>"You sure my friend?  I would think you tired," McMad questioned.<br>"I am sure.  Please join the others," he assured.<br>"Maybe I can get some boar while it is warm.  I will speak with you tommorow my friend", as McMad made his way.<br>He smiled as he looked out upon the vastness of the darkness.  It was a cold night.  He had set his gaze.  His thoughts again turned toward her.  He saw her eyes before him.  Lost as he kept his gaze.  He looked at the fields of green growing on a hilly landscape.  Clouds chasing.  Winds blowing.  Blowing so that her cape moved.  So gently.  She began to turn.  The wind singing a soft melody in the tall grass.  His heart was warm.  His eyes searching, watching.  Turning slowing, she moved.  Her eyes.  He saw forever.  He saw all things.  They called to him.  <br><br>The frost had begun to collect on his cape as the fires died down in the Keep.  He stood watch.<br><br></font></td>
